Finally, the produced cost of CO2 uses the cost of capturing CO2 and adjusts for additional CO2 captured onsite, specifically CO2 captured from natural gas combustion in the oxy-fired calcination unit. Ultimately, the produced cost of CO2 is equivalent to the price at which CO2 could be sold for the process to break-even. This is described in Eq. (6).6Producedcost[$tCO2−1]=Processcost[$]CO2capturefromair[tCO2]+additionalCO2capturedbyprocess[tCO2].\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
